      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'The first proper interaction was coloured keys. The key pickup script now supports four colours: blue, green, red, and yellow. The player can collect them, the key disappears, and the game logs what was collected. That gave the project its first small piece of actual gameplay state.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'That immediately led to the next design decision: how should the player interact with the world? Do we use one button for everything, switching between fire and action depending on context, or do we map separate buttons? It took about thirty seconds to remember we are not trapped in the 8-bit era anymore. The game can have a ',
          },
          {
            text: 'Fire',
            strong: true,
          },
          {
            text: ' button and an ',
          },
          {
            text: 'Interact',
            strong: true,
          },
          {
            text: ' button. Nobody wants to blast a meanie and accidentally have the game interpret that as, “please operate this nearby delivery machine.”',
          },
