      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'Getting that wired was more fiddly than it should have been. UI Toolkit needs the ',
          },
          {
            text: 'UIDocument',
            code: true,
          },
          {
            text: ' to display the UXML, a controller script to find and update named elements, and then the player inventory needs a reference to that controller. It works, but the setup feels like plugging a kettle into a toaster through a fax machine. Scotch would not have been an unreasonable thought at 05:35.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'paragraph',
        content: [
          {
            text: 'Still, it works. The player collects keys, the inventory records them, the HUD displays them, and the notice area remains free for gameplay messages. That is a proper little foundation. Tomorrow’s fun should be opening the lock box. In very technical terms: are you the Keymaster? If yes, open the box and get the package.',
          },
        ],
      },
      {
        type: 'next',
        title: 'Opening the Box',
        text: 'Use the key inventory to interact with matching lock boxes. The first version only needs to check whether the player has the correct key, swap the lock box sprite to the unlocked version, and log the result. Package release can come after the lock box state works.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
  chapter: "007",
  title: "Camera Follow, Moving Meanies, and Death Zones",
  date: "2026-06-02",
  stage: "Gameplay systems",
